it":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Timezone-aware scheduling produces correct run times across DST spring-forward and fall-back transitions","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the scheduling algorithm's handling of a specific, deterministic timezone rule — the spring-forward gap and the fall-back ambiguity. This is a single function's logic interacting with the in-process timezone database (zoneinfo / pytz). REAL-INFRA: Timezone data is embedded in the standard library; no OS primitives, real network, or subprocess is required. The failure appears if the algorithm mis-handles the fold/gap flag, which is fully reproducible in-process. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the timezone library would hide the real failure, so the timezone library must be used for real — but that is still in-process. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected — real OS clock is not consulted; fixed wall-clock inputs are used. Integration rejected — no second module boundary mediates the DST computation.","test_description":"Call the timezone-aware next-run-time function with a '30 2 * * *' (2:30 AM) expression anchored to a fixed UTC time just before the spring-forward transition in a well-known timezone (e.g., America/New_York). Assert the function skips the non-existent 2:30 AM and returns the next valid occurrence. Repeat for fall-back: assert the function returns exactly one occurrence of the ambiguous 2:30 AM (not two), using the correct fold resolution as specified by the job config.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Engine applies skip-or-backfill missed-run policy when the computed next run time has already passed","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior says 'the engine determines' — the failure is in how the orchestration layer reads a job's policy config and routes to skip vs backfill. A unit test of the policy decision function alone with a pre-computed 'is_late' boolean would not catch a wiring bug where the engine reads the wrong config field or passes a stale timestamp to the policy. The failure appears at the module boundary between the scheduler engine, the job-config reader, and the policy evaluator. REAL-INFRA: No OS or network needed; an in-process fake clock (fixed 'now') is sufficient and will expose the real failure. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected — no subprocess or real network is involved. Unit rejected — the engine's routing logic requires the job config reader to be wired in for the failure to be observable.","test_description":"Construct a job with a known next-run-time set 10 minutes in the past. Inject a fixed 'now' clock. Run the engine's missed-run resolution step with the job configured to 'skip' and verify the job is marked skipped with no execution queued. Repeat with the same job configured to 'backfill' and verify exactly one backfill execution is queued for the missed slot. Confirm that a job whose next-run-time is in the future is unaffected by either policy branch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9861,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9861},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"076afa1b-187c-402e-b47f-4c11577a6e30","uuid":"e1394e0d-41ba-4363-b5e6-e2112cf08360"}
